ce:section.ce:para:
The antifungal efficacy of both biologically and chemically synthesized C-dots was rigorously evaluated against clinical isolates of Candida auris using the micro-broth dilution method (Fig. 5
                           ai-aii) [46,47]. The resazurin assay served as the primary analytical tool to determine the MIC and MFC, based on a metabolic activity-dependent color change from purple to pink. To highlight the effectiveness of this method for evaluating antifungal properties, complete fungicidal activity was observed within 24 h of incubation. Initially, the antifungal potential of chemically synthesized C-dots was examined against C. auris isolates (NCCPF-470197, NCCPF-470200, and NCCPF-470203). The results revealed that these chemically synthesized C-dots exhibited no antifungal activity, as neither MIC nor MFC values were measurable (Fig. 5bi-bii). Furthermore, no inhibitory or fungicidal effects were observed, suggesting a lack of efficacy against C. auris under the tested conditions. Since the Trillium govanianum rhizomes are rich in the bioactive compounds and are well known for their medicinal properties. Therefore, preliminary experiments were carried out on the Trillium govanianum plant extract, to determine its antifungal potential. The result revealed that the extract demonstrated significant fungicidal activity against all three C. auris isolates. The MFC was determined to be 64 mg/mL for C. auris NCCPF-470197 and NCCPF-470200, while a lower MFC of 32 mg/mL was observed for C. auris NCCPF-470203 (Fig. 5ci-cii). These findings highlight the differential antifungal potency of the extract across various clinical isolates (Table 3
                           ). Finally, N-doped C-dots synthesized from Trillium govanianum rhizomes were evaluated for their antifungal capacity against clinical isolates of C. auris. Complete fungicidal activity was achieved after 24 h of incubation, with the MFC recorded at 1.25 mg/mL for all three isolates (C. auris NCCPF-470197, NCCPF-470200, and NCCPF-470203). Further, the MIC was identified at a concentration of 0.625 mg/mL, effectively inhibiting the growth of all tested isolates (Fig. 5di-dii). To validate these findings, a series of custom interpolated concentrations ranging from 0.5 to 1.5 mg/mL was employed. The results consistently supported the initially determined MIC and MFC values which confirmed the accuracy and broad-spectrum antifungal activity of the synthesized N-doped C-dots. Additionally, the obtained results underscore the superior antifungal potential of biologically synthesized C-dots from Trillium govanianum in comparison to their chemically synthesized counterparts and the crude plant extract, establishing their promise as potent antifungal agents.
